<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="865" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d865">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111 A.R.–Subs/19</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hornibrook</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2355</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-13">July 13,
                                1940</date>.<lb/>[Received July 22.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the
                            Department’s circular telegram of June 13, 8 p.m., concerning the
                            possible adoption by the American Republics of a uniform policy with
                            regard to the exclusion of belligerent submarines from the ports and
                            territorial waters of these republics, and to inform the Department that
                            this matter was brought to the attention of the Minister of Foreign
                            Affairs on June 14. <pb facs="0797" n="785" xml:id="pg_785"/> After
                            subsequently pressing several times for a reply, the Minister informed
                            the Legation in a note dated July 1 that the matter had been referred to
                            the Ministry of Public Security for consideration. Nothing further on
                            the subject has been heard from the Foreign Office since that time.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. H. Hornibrook</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>